{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489577"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:21:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:21:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"694"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/694"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.61,0.18,0.07,0.08,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"694"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114511"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/694"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"694"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96512"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1634"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1681"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48069"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114511"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man is being reassessed after he has a screening PSA performed which showed a PSA of 9 \u00b5g/L. This was followed by a TRUS biopsy which showed a small focus of Gleason 6 prostate cancer. His medical history includes two coronary artery bypass grafts, poorly controlled diabetes and advanced chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Watchful waiting","PSA monitoring","Brachytherapy","Prostatectomy","Goserelin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis asymptomatic patient with a localised Gleason 6 prostate cancer and a PSA of \u0026lt;10 \u00b5g/L most likely has low-risk prostate cancer. Evidence suggests that, when compared to observation alone, active management in patients with low-risk prostate cancer and a life expectancy  of \u0026lt;10 years does not improve mortality. Thus, the recommendation is for active surveillance. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, this 78-year-old patient has multiple co-morbid conditions and is of advanced age - a more active approach, such as PSA monitoring, is very unlikely to influence any change in the most sensible plan of management in this unfit individual. He should be managed with \u003Cstrong\u003Ewatchful waiting. \u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActive intervention and monitoring (e.g. \u003Cstrong\u003EPSA monitoring, brachytherapy, prostatectomy, \u003C/strong\u003Eor \u003Cstrong\u003Egoserelin\u003C/strong\u003E) is unnecessarily invasive for this patient. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Active surveillance is recommended for asymptomatic patients with a life expectancy of \u003C10 years."],"references":["Romero-Otero J, Garc\u00eda-G\u00f3mez B, Duarte-Ojeda J, Rodr\u00edguez-Antol\u00edn A, Vilaseca A, Carlsson S et al. Active surveillance for prostate cancer. International Journal of Urology. 2015;23(3):211-218.","Duchesne G. Localised prostate cancer - current treatment options. Aust Fam Physician. 2011 Oct;40(10):768-71. PMID: 22003477.","Wang G, Zhao D, Spring D, DePinho R. Genetics and biology of prostate cancer. Genes \u0026 Development. 2018;32(17-18):1105-1140."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96512"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"694"}},"s